<subsection xml:id="subsec-surface-area-of-composite-solids" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
    <title>Surface Area of Composite Solids</title>
    <objectives component="outcomes">
        <introduction>
            <dl>
                <li>
                    <title>Strand</title>
                    <p>
                        2.0 Measurements and Geometry
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <title>Sub-Strand</title>
                    <p>
                        2.7 Surface Area
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <title>Specific Learning Outcomes</title>
                    <ul>
                        <li>Calculate the volume of prisms, pyramids, cones, frustums and spheres</li>
                        <li>Explore the use of the surface area and volume of solids in real-life situations</li>
                    </ul>
                </li>
                <li component="lesson-plan">
                    <title>Grade Level</title>
                    <p>
                        10
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li component="lesson-plan">
                    <title>Estimated Duration</title>
                    <p>
                        40 minutes
                    </p>
                </li>
            </dl>
        </introduction>
        <introduction component="lesson-plan">
            <p> Upon completion of this lesson, learners will be able to:
            <ol>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        <alert>Know (Conceptual Understanding):</alert> Define a composite solid as a shape formed by combining two or more basic solids. State the key principle: Surface Area of Composite Solid <m>=</m> Sum of all visible surfaces. Identify hidden surfaces where solids connect.
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        <alert>Do (Procedural Skill):</alert> Identify visible and hidden surfaces of composite solids. Calculate the surface area of each component separately. Combine individual surface areas, excluding hidden surfaces, to find the total surface area.
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        <alert>Apply (Application/Problem-Solving):</alert> Solve real-world problems involving composite solid surface areas, such as calculating paint coverage, material costs, and construction requirements for objects like buildings, containers, and toys.
                    </p>
                </li>
            </ol>
            </p>
        </introduction>
    </objectives>
        <axiom component="resources">
        <!-- Link to blurb -->
        <xi:include href="../../resources-blurb-lesson.ptx" />

        <sbsgroup widths="45% 45%" margins="2% 2%">
            <sidebyside>
                <p>
                    <dataurl source="lesson_plans/measurements-and-geometry/surface-area/surface-area-of-composite-solids.pdf"> Lesson Plan </dataurl>
                </p>
                <p>
                    <dataurl source="lesson_plans/measurements-and-geometry/surface-area/step-by-step-guide_surface-area-of-composite-solids.pdf"> Step-by-Step Guide </dataurl>
                </p>
            </sidebyside>
        </sbsgroup>
    </axiom>
    <xi:include href="../../resources-materials.ptx" />

    <axiom component="lesson-plan">
        <title>Phase 1: Problem-Solving and Discovery</title>
        <p>
            <alert>Suggested Time:</alert> 15 minutes
        </p>
        <p>
            <alert>Grouping:</alert> Groups of 3–4
        </p>
        <p>
            <alert>Activity:</alert> Tree Model Surface Area
        </p>
        <p>
            <alert>Teacher Prompts:</alert>
            <ul>
                <li><p><q>What surfaces are visible in your tree model?</q></p></li>
                <li><p><q>Which surfaces are hidden? Why don’t we count them?</q></p></li>
                <li><p><q>What happens if the cone is bigger than the cylinder?</q></p></li>
                <li><p><q>How would the surface area change if the tree had branches modelled as small cylinders?</q></p></li>
            </ul>
        </p>
        <p>
            <alert>Teacher Role During Discovery:</alert>
            <ul>
                <li><p>Circulate among groups, ensuring students understand how to build the tree model.</p></li>
                <li><p>Ask probing questions: <q>What surfaces are visible? Which surfaces are hidden?</q></p></li>
                <li><p>For struggling groups: <q>Let us start by finding the lateral area of the cylinder. Then find the base area. What about the cone?</q></p></li>
                <li><p>For early finishers: <q>How would the surface area change if you used a hemisphere instead of a cone?</q></p></li>
                <li><p>Identify 2–3 groups with clear findings to share with the class.</p></li>
            </ul>
        </p>
    </axiom>


     
	 	<activity xml:id="auto_an3e1tvf">
		<statement>
			<p xml:id="auto_11oz5l9r">
				<m>\textbf{Tree Model Surface Area}</m>
			</p>
			<p xml:id="auto_dw9m04ah">
				Theme: Modeling a tree using a cylinder \<m>textbf{trunk}</m> and hemisphere <m>\textbf{tree top}</m> or cone <m>\textbf{pine tree top}</m>
			</p>
			<p xml:id="auto_jkk10o50">
				We  will model a tree trunk as a composite solid, then calculate the total surface area, excluding the part where the top and trunk connect.
			</p>
			<p xml:id="auto_t1gg8ctc">
				<ul xml:id="auto_yvfctbmq">
					<li xml:id="auto_14bnk4v5">
						<p xml:id="auto_4zwlqarz">
							<m>\textbf{Materials needed:}</m>
						</p>
					</li>
					<li xml:id="auto_m062z1b7">
						<p xml:id="auto_i0jj6qg6">
							Nets or templates for:
						</p>	
						<p xml:id="auto_9v0xzbte">
							 Cylinder (tree trunk)
						</p>
						<p xml:id="auto_agvtmaea">
							 Cone or hemisphere (tree top)
						</p>   
					</li>
					<li xml:id="auto_n0a7qq83">
						<p xml:id="auto_wqu3zmil">
							Scissors, glue or tape
						</p>
					</li>
					<li xml:id="auto_y52pu93h">
						<p xml:id="auto_z8l3psru">
							Rulers and string
						</p>
						<p xml:id="auto_fhyttu4t">
							 Step-by-Step Instructions.
						</p>
						<p xml:id="auto_x4nl8mvc">
							1. Create the Model
						</p>
					</li>
					<li xml:id="auto_o1gzkdnm">
						<p xml:id="auto_cehlokip">
							Each student or group builds a tree model using
						</p>
					</li>
					<li xml:id="auto_5iv30mo7">
						<p xml:id="auto_ayg2ipc3">
							A cylinder for the trunk
						</p>
					</li>
					<li xml:id="auto_xet74nhu">
						<p xml:id="auto_lnrlw48y">

                            Either a cone (pine tree) or a hemisphere (bushy tree) for the top
							
						</p>
						<p xml:id="auto_sam9uwu5">
							For example, a pine tree would be a cone on top of a cylinder.
						</p>
						<p xml:id="auto_xjdj84tt">
							2. Label Dimensions
						</p>
					</li>
					<li xml:id="auto_51nv3fyl">
						<p xml:id="auto_4j7x0grt">
							Measure and label your dimensions (or give them pre-set values). For example:
                        </p>
							<p xml:id="auto_29oj0ytq">	♦ Radius of trunk = 3 cm</p>

							<p xml:id="auto_c3ykadja">	♦ Height of trunk = 10 cm</p>

							<p xml:id="auto_4uwy4peo">	♦ Radius of cone = 3 cm</p>

							<p xml:id="auto_uoqznhyn">	♦ Slant height of cone = 5 cm
						</p>
						<p xml:id="auto_f7qr7laf">
							3. Surface Area Calculation
						</p>
					</li>
					<li xml:id="auto_vtssp7rd">
						<p xml:id="auto_yt4ri3si">
							Surface area of cylinder:

							♦ Lateral area: <m>2 \pi r h</m>

							♦ Bottom circle: <m>\pi r2</m>

							♦ Do NOT count the top circle — it is covered by the cone
						</p>
					</li>
					<li xml:id="auto_y0ktn9kq">
						<p xml:id="auto_l60mivv9">
							Surface area of cone:
						</p>
						<p xml:id="auto_7ae6lvk7">
							♦ Lateral area: <m>2 \pi r \ell</m>
						</p>	
                        <p xml:id="auto_m6vu2sr9">
						♦ Do NOT count the base of the cone — it is attached to the trunk
                        </p>
						<p xml:id="auto_gxme598e">
						♦ Add all visible surfaces:
						</p>
						<p xml:id="auto_ex4sg377">
						♦ <m>\text{S.A}_{\text{total}} = \textbf{Lateral area of cone} + \textbf{Lateral area of cylinder} + \textbf{Base of cylinder}</m>
						</p>
					</li>
					<li xml:id="auto_bbsqndre">
						<p xml:id="auto_ixxbkvsx">
							Sample Calculation:
                        </p>
						<p xml:id="auto_edyd6hoq">
                          With the above values:
                        </p>
						<p xml:id="auto_rzy7s697">
						Cylinder lateral: <m>2\pi \times (3 \, \text{cm})\times(10 \, \text{cm}) = 60 \, \text{cm} \times 3.14 =188.40 \, \text{cm}^2</m>
                         </p>
						 <p xml:id="auto_b0zgetdw">
						Cylinder base: <m>\pi \times (3 \, \text{cm})^2 =9 \, \text{cm} \times 3.14 = 28.26\, \text{cm}^2</m>
                          </p>
						  <p xml:id="auto_j6xvrdzu">
						Cone lateral: <m>\pi (3 \, \text{cm}) \times (5 \, \text{cm}) = 15 \, \text{cm} \times 3.14 = 47.10 \,\text{cm}^2</m>
						</p>
						<p xml:id="auto_vlotkhta">
							<m>S.A = 188.40 \, \text{cm}^2 + 28.26\, \text{cm}^2 + 47.10 \,\text{cm}^2 = 263.76 \, \text{cm}^2</m>
						</p>
					</li>
					<li xml:id="auto_cy5lnsi6">
						<p xml:id="auto_9xoa4uo3">
							<m>\textbf{Study Questions}</m>
						</p>
						<p xml:id="auto_h0eiqg30">
                          Why don’t we count the base of the cone or the top of the cylinder?
						</p>
						<p xml:id="auto_cvufc322">
							What happens if the cone is bigger than the cylinder?
						</p>
						<p xml:id="auto_f9ahy0os">
							How would the surface area change if the tree had branches modeled as small cylinders?
						</p>
					</li>
				</ul>
			</p>
		</statement>
	</activity>
	
	   <p xml:id="auto_vg8dpnua">
		 A <m>\textbf{Solid}</m> is a three dimensional shape. <m> \textbf{Solids}</m> are objects with three dimensions i.e Width, Length and Height and they have surface area and volumes.. 
	 </p>
    <p xml:id="auto_1qkugc5n">
      <m>\textbf{Area of composite solids} </m>
	</p>
	<p xml:id="auto_mk9g8y0z">
		When two or more different solids are placed together, the result is composite solids. The surface area of a composite solids can be found by adding areas of the parts of the solids.
	</p>

	<insight>
		<p>
			<term>What is a Composite Solid?</term> A solid is a three-dimensional shape. Solids are objects with three dimensions: Width, Length, and Height. They have surface area and volumes.
		</p>
		<p>
			When two or more different solids are placed together, the result is composite solids. The surface area of composite solids can be found by adding areas of the parts of the solids, excluding hidden surfaces where the solids connect.
		</p>
		<p>
			<term>Key Principle:</term>
		</p>
		<p>
			Surface Area of Composite Solid <m>=</m> Sum of all visible surfaces
		</p>
		<p>
			<term>Important:</term> Do NOT count surfaces that are hidden or covered by other parts of the composite solid.
		</p>
		<p>
			<term>Examples is a Cone on Top of Cylinder</term>
		</p>
		<image width="50%">
			<latex-image label="cone_on_cylinder">
				\begin{tikzpicture}[scale=0.8]
				\draw (0,0) ellipse (2 and 0.6);
				\draw (-2,0) -- (-2,-4);
				\draw (2,0) -- (2,-4);
				\draw (-2,-4) arc (180:360:2 and 0.6);
				\draw[dashed] (2,-4) arc (0:180:2 and 0.6);
				\draw (-2,0) -- (0,3);
				\draw (2,0) -- (0,3);
				\draw (0,0) ellipse (2 and 0.6);
				\node at (0,3.5) {Cone};
				\node at (0,-4.8) {Cylinder};
				\end{tikzpicture}
    		</latex-image>
		</image>
		<p>
			<ol marker="(a)">
				<li>
					<p>
						<term>Visible surfaces:</term>
					</p>
					<p>
						Lateral surface of cone
					</p>
					<p>
						Lateral surface of cylinder
					</p>
					<p>
						Base of cylinder
					</p>
				</li>
				<li>
					<p>
						<term>Hidden surfaces (DO NOT count):</term>
					</p>
					<p>
						Base of cone (attached to cylinder)
					</p>
					<p>
						Top of cylinder (covered by cone)
					</p>
				</li>
			</ol>
		</p>
		<p>
			<term>Scaffolding Strategies to Address Misconceptions:</term>
		</p>
		<tabular bottom="medium" top="medium" right="medium" left="medium">
			<row header="yes">
				<cell>Misconception</cell>
				<cell>Clarification</cell>
			</row>
			<row>
				<cell>I should add the surface areas of both solids completely</cell>
				<cell>No, you must exclude hidden surfaces where the solids connect</cell>
			</row>
			<row>
				<cell>All surfaces are visible</cell>
				<cell>No, some surfaces are hidden when solids are joined together</cell>
			</row>
			<row>
				<cell>I can just use one formula</cell>
				<cell>No, you must calculate the surface area of each part separately, then add them together</cell>
			</row>
			<row>
				<cell>The order of calculation does not matter</cell>
				<cell>While the order does not affect the final answer, it is best to work systematically: identify all visible surfaces, calculate each area, then sum them</cell>
			</row>
		</tabular>
	</insight>

    <axiom component="lesson-plan">
        <title>Phase 2: Structured Instruction</title>
        <p>
            <alert>Suggested Time:</alert> 10 minutes
        </p>
        <p>
            <alert>Grouping:</alert> Whole class
        </p>
        <p>
            <alert>Teacher Guidance:</alert> After students have completed the anchor activity and shared their findings, formalise the concept of composite solids. Direct learners’ attention to the Key Takeaway box above.
        </p>
        <p>
            <alert>Prompting Questions:</alert>
            <ul>
                <li><p><q>Should I add the surface areas of both solids completely?</q> (No — exclude hidden surfaces.)</p></li>
                <li><p><q>Are all surfaces visible?</q> (No — some are hidden where solids connect.)</p></li>
                <li><p><q>Can I just use one formula?</q> (No — calculate each part separately, then add.)</p></li>
            </ul>
        </p>
    </axiom>

    <axiom component="lesson-plan">
        <title>Phase 3: Practice and Application</title>
        <p>
            <alert>Suggested Time:</alert> 10 minutes
        </p>
        <p>
            <alert>Grouping:</alert> Individual, then pairs to compare
        </p>
        <p>
            <alert>Teacher Guidance:</alert> Walk learners through the worked examples that follow. For each example, have learners first identify the visible and hidden surfaces before calculating. Emphasise the systematic approach: identify surfaces, calculate each area, then sum.
        </p>
    </axiom>

    
<example xml:id="auto_xgw7h4e6">
	<statement>
		<sidebyside>
		 <p xml:id="auto_n2obio97">
			Find the surface area of the figure alongside. Leave your answer in <m>\text{m}^2</m>
		 </p>	
		 </sidebyside>	
		</statement>
		<solution>
		<image width="50%">
		<latex-image label="cone-cylinder">
			\begin{tikzpicture}[rotate=90]
				% Set background color
				<!-- \fill[cyan!30] (-3,-1) rectangle (3,9); -->
				
				% Fill the cylinder with a light blue shade
				\draw[thick] (-2,0) rectangle (2,5);
				\draw[thick] (0,5) ellipse (2cm and 0.5cm);
				\draw[dashed] (0,0) ellipse (2cm and 0.5cm);
				% Draw the base ellipse
				\draw[dashed] (0,0) ellipse (2cm and 0.5cm);
				
				% Draw the vertical sides of the cylinder
				\draw[thick] (-2,0) -- (-2,5);
				\draw[thick] (2,0) -- (2,5);
				
				% Draw the top ellipse of the cylinder
				\draw (0,5) ellipse (2cm and 0.5cm);
				
				% Draw the conical top
				\draw (-2,5) -- (0,8);
				\draw (2,5) -- (0,8);
				
				% Dashed line for height of cone
				\draw[dashed] (0,8) -- (0,5);
				\draw[dashed] (0,5)--(2,5);
				\draw[dashed] (0,0) --(2,0);
				
				% Label dimensions
				\node[above] at (2,2.5) {\large 50 cm};
				\node[right] at (1,-1) {\large 40 cm};
				\node[below] at (1,6.5) {\large 30 cm};
    
			\end{tikzpicture}
		</latex-image>
		</image>
		<p xml:id="auto_j1zwuiwa">
			Surface Area of a cone.
			<md>
				<mrow>CSA_{\text{cone}} = \amp \pi r \times ( \ell = \sqrt{r^2 +h^2} )</mrow>
				<mrow> = \amp 3.14 \times (40 \,\text{cm}) \times \sqrt{(40)^2 \, \text{cm} + (30)^2 \, \text{cm}} </mrow>
				<mrow> = \amp 3.14 \times 40 \, \text{cm} \times 50 \, \text{cm}</mrow>
				<mrow> = \amp 125.60 \times 50  </mrow> 
				<mrow> = \amp 6,280 \text{cm}^2 </mrow>
			</md>
		</p>
		<p xml:id="auto_nz6a18lq">
			Curved Surface Area of the Cylinder
			<md>
				<mrow>CSA_{\text{cylinder}} = \amp  2\pi r \times h</mrow>
				<mrow> = \amp 2 \times 3.14 \times (40 \,\text{cm}) \times 50 \, \text{ cm} </mrow>
				<mrow> = \amp 2 \times 3.14 \times 40 \, \text{cm} \times 50 \, \text{cm}</mrow>
				<mrow> = \amp 251.20\, \text{cm}^2\times 50 \, \text{cm} </mrow> 
				<mrow> = \amp 12, 560 \,\text{cm}^2 </mrow>
			</md>
		</p>
		<p xml:id="auto_2gvdm3mh">
			Base Area of the Cylinder (since only the bottom is exposed)
			<md>
				<mrow> \text{Base Area} = \amp \pi r^2 </mrow>
				<mrow> = \amp \pi \times (40)^2 \, \text{cm} </mrow>
				<mrow> = \amp 5024 \, \text{cm}^2 </mrow>
			</md>

		</p>
		<p xml:id="auto_4qpp1cb4">
			Total Surface Area <m> = CSA_{\text{cylinder}} + CSA_{\text{cone}}  + \,\text{Base Area}  </m>
			<md>
				<mrow> = \amp 12, 560\, \text{cm}^2 + 6,280 \, \text{cm}^2 + 5024 \, \text{cm}^2   </mrow>
				<mrow> = \amp 23,864 \, \text{cm}^2 </mrow>
			</md> 
			Converting to <m> \text{m}^2 </m>
			<md>
				<mrow> 1 \text{m} = \amp 100 \, \text{cm}</mrow>
				<mrow> 1 \text{m}^2 = \amp 10,000\,  \text{cm}^2</mrow>
				<mrow> ?  \amp 23,864\, \text{cm}^2  </mrow>
				<mrow> = \amp 1\, \text{m} \times \frac{23,864\, \text{cm}^2} {10,000\, \text{cm}^2} </mrow>
				<mrow> = \amp  2.3864 \, \text{m}^2 </mrow>
				<mrow> = \amp 2.39\, \text{m}^2 \,\ \text{(to two d.p)}  </mrow>
			</md>
		</p>
		</solution>
	
	</example>
	<example>
		<statement>
			<p>
				A solid consists of a <term>cylinder</term> of radius <m>5</m> cm and height <m>12</m> cm, with a <term>hemisphere</term> of the same radius fixed on top.
			</p>
			<p>
				 Find the total surface area of the composite solid.
			</p>
			<image>
				<latex-image>
					\begin{tikzpicture}[scale=0.9]
					\draw (0,0) ellipse (2 and 0.6);
					\draw (2,0) -- (-2,-4);
					\draw (2,0) -- (2,-4);
					\draw (-2,-4) arc (180:360:2 and 0.6); 
					\draw[dashed] (2,-4) arc (0:180:2 and 0.6);
					\draw (-2,0) arc (180:0:2);

					\draw[dashed] (2,0) arc (0:180:2 and 0.6);
					\end{tikzpicture}
				</latex-image>
        	</image>
			

		</statement>
		<solution>
			<p>
				<ol marker="Step 1">
					<li>
						<p>
							<term>Identify visible surfaces.</term>
						</p>
						<p>
							Visible surfaces:
						</p>
						<p>
							<ol marker="(i)">
								<li>
									<p>
										Curved surface of the hemisphere
									</p>
									<p>
										Curved surface of the cylinder
									</p>
									<p>
										Base of the cylinder
									</p>
								</li>
							</ol>
						</p>
						<p>
							Hidden surfaces (not counted):
						</p>
						<p>
							<ol marker="(i)">
								<li>
									<p>
										Flat circular base of the hemisphere
									</p>
									<p>
										Top of the cylinder
									</p>
								</li>
							</ol>
						</p>
					</li>
					<li>
						<p>
							<term>Calculate each visible surface area.</term>
						</p>
						<p>
							Radius, <m>r = 5</m> cm, Height of cylinder, <m>h = 12</m> cm
						</p>
						<p>
							Curved surface area of cylinder:
						</p>
						<p>
							<m>2\pi rh = 2\pi(5)(12) = 120\pi</m>
						</p>
						<p>
							Curved surface area of hemisphere:
						</p>
						<p>
							<m>2\pi r^2 = 2\pi(5^2) = 50\pi</m>
						</p>
						<p>
							Area of base of cylinder:
						</p>
						<p>
							<m>\pi r^2 = \pi(5^2) = 25\pi</m>
						</p>
					</li>
					<li>
						<p>
							<term>Add all visible surfaces.</term>
						</p>
						<p>
							<m>120\pi + 50\pi + 25\pi = 195\pi</m>
						</p>
						<p>
							Therefore, the total surface area is:
						</p>
						<p>
							<m>195\pi \approx 612.61 \text{ cm}^2</m>
						</p>
					</li>
				</ol>
			</p>
		</solution>
	</example>

    <axiom component="lesson-plan">
        <title>Phase 4: Assessment</title>
        <p>
            <alert>Suggested Time:</alert> 5 minutes
        </p>
        <p>
            <alert>Grouping:</alert> Individual
        </p>
        <p>
            <alert>Exit Ticket:</alert> Students complete the following questions individually.
        </p>
        <p>
            <ol marker="1.">
                <li>
                    <p>A right circular ice cream cone with a radius of <m>3</m> cm and a height of <m>12</m> cm holds a half scoop of ice cream in the shape of a hemisphere on top. If the ice cream melts completely, will it fit inside the cone? Show all calculations.</p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>A lampshade is in the shape of a frustum of a cone. The top and bottom circular openings have diameters of <m>12</m> cm and <m>20</m> cm, respectively. If the slant height is <m>15</m> cm, find the lateral surface area.</p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>A birthday cake has a cylindrical base of radius <m>10</m> cm and height <m>15</m> cm. The top is shaped like a hemisphere with the same radius. Find the total volume of the cake.</p>
                </li>
            </ol>
        </p>
        <p>
            <alert>Answer Key (Teacher Reference):</alert>
        </p>
        <p>
            <ol marker="1.">
                <li>
                    <p>Volume of cone <m>= \frac{1}{3}\pi(3)^2(12) = 113.04 \text{ cm}^3</m>. Volume of hemisphere <m>= \frac{2}{3}\pi(3)^3 = 56.52 \text{ cm}^3</m>. Since <m>56.52 \lt 113.04</m>, yes, the ice cream fits.</p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>Lateral area <m>= \pi(R + r)\ell = 3.14 \times (10 + 6) \times 15 = 753.6 \text{ cm}^2</m>.</p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>Volume <m>= \pi r^2 h + \frac{2}{3}\pi r^3 = 3.14 \times 100 \times 15 + \frac{2}{3} \times 3.14 \times 1000 = 4710 + 2093.33 = 6803.33 \text{ cm}^3</m>.</p>
                </li>
            </ol>
        </p>
    </axiom>

	<exercises>
		<exercise>
			<statement>
				<p>
					The solid below is made of a cube and a square pyramid whose height is <m>33</m> cm and cube sides measures <m>14</m> cm. Find the surface area of the solid shown (give your answers to two decimal places).
				</p>
				<image width="100%">
				<latex-image label="trun">
					\begin{tikzpicture}[rotate=270]
						% Define colors
						\definecolor{mycube}{RGB}{144, 202, 249} % Light Blue for cube
						\definecolor{mypyramid}{RGB}{255, 183, 77} % Orange for pyramid
						
						% Draw Cube (Base)
						\fill[mycube] (-1,-1,0) -- (1,-1,0) -- (1,1,0) -- (-1,1,0) -- cycle;
						\fill[mycube] (-1,-1,2) -- (1,-1,2) -- (1,1,2) -- (-1,1,2) -- cycle;
						\fill[mycube,opacity=0.7] (-1,-1,0) -- (-1,-1,2) -- (-1,1,2) -- (-1,1,0) -- cycle;
						\fill[mycube,opacity=0.7] (1,-1,0) -- (1,-1,2) -- (1,1,2) -- (1,1,0) -- cycle;

						% Draw Cube (Outline)
						\draw (-1,-1,0) -- (1,-1,0) -- (1,1,0) -- (-1,1,0) -- cycle;
						\draw (-1,-1,2) -- (1,-1,2) -- (1,1,2) -- (-1,1,2) -- cycle;
						\draw (-1,-1,0) -- (-1,-1,2);
						\draw (1,-1,0) -- (1,-1,2);
						\draw (1,1,0) -- (1,1,2);
						\draw (-1,1,0) -- (-1,1,2);

						% Draw Pyramid (on top of cube)
						\fill[mypyramid] (-1,-1,2) -- (0,0,6) -- (1,-1,2) -- cycle;
						\fill[mypyramid,opacity=0.7] (-1,1,2) -- (0,0,6) -- (1,1,2) -- cycle;
						\fill[mypyramid,opacity=0.7] (-1,-1,2) -- (0,0,6) -- (-1,1,2) -- cycle;
						\fill[mypyramid,opacity=0.7] (1,-1,2) -- (0,0,6) -- (1,1,2) -- cycle;

						% Draw Pyramid (Outline)
						\draw (-1,-1,2) -- (0,0,6) -- (1,-1,2);
						\draw (-1,1,2) -- (0,0,6) -- (1,1,2);
						\draw[dashed] (0,0,6) -- (0,0,2);

						% Dimension labels
						\draw[&lt;-&gt;] (1.5,-1,0) -- (1.5,1,0);
						\node[above] at (1.5,0,0) {\large 14 cm};

						\draw[&lt;-&gt;] (1.5,1,1) -- (1.5,1,9);
						\node[right] at (1.5,0.8,5.5) {\large 33 cm};

					\end{tikzpicture}
				</latex-image>
				</image>
			</statement>
			<answer>
				<p>
					<m>1924.44 \;\text{cm}^2</m>
				</p>
			</answer>
		</exercise>
		<exercise>
			<statement>
				<p>
					Calculate the surface area of the given solid.
				</p>
				<image width="50%">
				<latex-image label="frustrum-cube-cube">
					\begin{tikzpicture}[rotate=90]
						% Bottom hemisphere (correct semicircle)
							\draw[thick] (-3,0) arc (180:360:3 and 1.5);
							
							% Cylinder body
							\draw[thick] (-3,0) -- (-3,4);
							\draw[thick] (3,0) -- (3,4);
							\draw[thick] (-3,4) -- (3,4);
							\draw[thick] (-3,0) -- (3,0);
							
							% Top hemisphere (correct semicircle)
							\draw[thick] (3,4) arc (0:180:3 and 1.5);
							
							% Total height dimension
							\draw[&lt;-&gt;] (-3.5,0) -- node[below] {11 m} (-3.5,4);
							
							% Lower diameter dimension
							\draw[&lt;-&gt;] (-3,-0.2) -- node[right] {6 m} (3,-0.2);
					\end{tikzpicture}
				</latex-image>
				</image>
			</statement>
			<answer>
				<p>
					<m>320.52 \;\text{m}^2</m>
				</p>
			</answer>
		</exercise>
		<exercise>
			<statement>
				<p>
					A lampshade is in the shape of a frustum of a cone. The top and bottom circular openings have diameters of <m>12</m> cm and <m>20</m> cm, respectively. If the slant height is <m>15</m> cm, find the lateral surface area of the lampshade.
				</p>
			</statement>
			<answer>
				<p>
					<m>753.6 \;\text{cm}^2</m>
				</p>
			</answer>
		</exercise>
		<exercise>
			<statement>
				<p>
					Mogaka a grade <m>10</m> student was trying to sketch an image of a ice cream cone container with icecream. Find the surface area of the sketched image.
				</p>
				<image width="45%">
				<latex-image label="truncated-cone-exercise">
					\begin{tikzpicture}
						% Draw the base circle (equator)
						\draw[thick] (0,0) ellipse (2 and 1);
						
						% Draw the semicircle (hemisphere) starting from -2
						\draw[thick] (-2,0) arc (180:360:2);
						
						% Vertical radius
						\draw[dashed] (-2,0) --(0,0) -- (0,5);
						\draw[thick]  (-1.99,0.2) --(0,5) --(2,0);
						
						% Labeling
						<!-- \node[below] at (0,-1.2) {Base semi-Circle}; -->
						\node[right] at (-1.6,0.5) { $r=5$};
						\node[right] at (0,2) { $h =10$};
						<!-- \node[right] at (-3,2.5) {Slanted height }; -->
						\node[below,rotate=50] at (-1.7,2.3) {$\ell = 15 cm$};
					\end{tikzpicture}
				</latex-image>
				</image>
			</statement>
			<answer>
				<p>
					<m>392.5 \;\text{cm}^2</m>
				</p>
			</answer>
		</exercise>
		<exercise>
			<statement>
				<p>
					A goblet consists of a hemisphere on top of a cylindrical base. The hemisphere has a radius of <m>5</m> cm, and the cylinder has the same radius with a height of <m>12</m> cm. Find the surface of the goblet.
				</p>
			</statement>
			<answer>
				<p>
					<m>533.8 \;\text{cm}^2</m>
				</p>
			</answer>
		</exercise>
	</exercises>


    


